To handle time data correctly in a PLCnext application, use the standard time library in C++ (e.g., `<chrono>` or `time.h`) or PLCnext APIs. Be aware of timezone settings and consider using UTC for consistent data handling across systems.

For example, you can use the `<chrono>` library to work with time points and durations:

```cpp
#include <chrono>

int main() {
    // Get the current time point
    auto now = std::chrono::system_clock::now();

    // Convert to local time
    auto now_local = std::chrono::system_clock::to_time_t(now);

    // Use a timezone-aware library like ICU or Boost.DateTime for more accurate conversions

    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use the PLCnext APIs to handle time-related operations. For example:

```cpp
#include "plcnext.h"

int main() {
    // Get the current timestamp
    uint32_t timestamp = plcGetTimestamp();

    // Convert to UTC time
    uint32_t utc_timestamp = timestamp;

    return 0;
}
```

When working with PROFINET data, ensure that the monitor time is at least 24 ms. The monitor time is the product of 'Reduction ratio' and 'Monitor factor' (in PLCnext Engineer: 'Profinet' editor group, 'Interface list' editor).

In PLCnext Engineer, when setting date/time via PLCnext Engineer and immediately shutting off the power supply, the date/time setting did not become effective. This is a known issue in older versions of PLCnext Engineer. To resolve this, update to the latest version of PLCnext Engineer or use a different method for setting date/time.

Remember to consider timezone settings when handling time data in your PLCnext application. Using UTC can help ensure consistent data handling across systems.

